# Stack Decisions Reference

Use this rule when implementing features, adding dependencies, or proposing technical alternatives.

## Core Rule

Stack and tooling decisions are documented in `docs/architecture/STACK.md`.

Before proposing or introducing a library, framework, or tool, consult STACK.md to check if a decision already exists.

## Locked Decisions (Summary)

The following areas have explicit decisions that should not be changed without strong justification and explicit approval:

| Area | Decision | Reference |
|------|----------|-----------|
| Mobile framework | React Native | STACK.md §Mobile layer |
| Backend runtime | Node.js LTS | STACK.md §Core stack |
| Database | PostgreSQL (Neon) | STACK.md §Core stack |
| API style | REST, JSON | STACK.md §Backend API |
| Request/response validation | Zod or equivalent | STACK.md §Backend API |
| Logging | Pino or structured JSON | STACK.md §Backend API |
| Test (backend) | Jest or Vitest | STACK.md §Core stack |
| Test (mobile) | Jest + React Native Testing Library | STACK.md §Core stack |
| Auth | OAuth (Google, Apple) and/or custom | STACK.md §Auth and integrations |
| Voice input | Platform APIs + voice-to-text service (e.g. Google Speech-to-Text) | STACK.md §Mobile layer |

## When Implementing

When implementing:

- use the locked decisions; do not propose alternatives without explicit approval
- follow established patterns from existing code
- if a new category requires a tool decision, propose it explicitly and update STACK.md after approval

## When Reviewing

When reviewing code that introduces new dependencies:

- verify the dependency aligns with STACK.md
- reject unapproved alternatives unless there is explicit justification
- ensure new decisions are documented before merging

## Exception Process

If a locked decision needs to change:

1. document the problem with the current choice
2. propose the alternative explicitly
3. update STACK.md after approval
4. create an ADR if the change is significant

## Final Rule

Consult STACK.md before implementing. Use what is decided. Propose changes explicitly, not implicitly through implementation.
